{
  "texts": [
    "Polarization of the electorate in regime (ii) is driven by the fact that agents receive more signals about the political parties, which naturally induces greater movements in their beliefs via Bayesian updating.",
    "While some agents become more moderate as a result of political advertising, the average movement of beliefs is toward the extremes.",
    "This can be seen from the fact that if all agents were sophisticated, advertising would induce a mean-preserving spread of beliefs (which follows from the Martingale property of Bayesian beliefs).",
    "However, with naïve agents, belief movements are more pronounced and have a positive drift toward more extreme positions given the misspecification about the informativeness of political ads.",
    "Then from Lemma 1, such transitions to more extreme ideologies by the electorate also leads the parties to anchor to more polarizing positions as a result."
  ]
}